TL;DR: Sent both of my children to the hospital.  Both of my toddlers have severe peanut allergies, but neither reacts to trace amounts. Cross-contact (poor kitchen practices, sharing a space with someone who has eaten peanuts) has never been an issue. They do just fine on the CTA, at public parks and libraries, and at friends’ houses.  There’s a sign on the way in to mention allergies, suggesting some level of food allergy awareness. My husband mentioned the severe peanut allergy when ordering.  Both of my children experienced severe allergic reactions. Not only did they almost die, their lives were shortened by the damage to their hearts and lungs and we will be paying thousands of dollars for their medical care.  Food allergy families should avoid this restaurant.

I remember when I first started visiting this restaurant back in the 80, the food was excellent, plentiful and reasonable, I don't know if the owner Retired, or got I'll,  but that's when the restaurant did a whole 360. The food is still edible, but not the same quality. Now it seems like what they throw together is what u get. I always order pepper steak and chicken fried rice. For starts the amount of chicken in the fried rice is invisible, might as well order plain fried rice it's cheaper and the steak if I may call it that is very tough, but you do get a lot of peppers and onions, how big of a difference time makes, and the one on 87th and Dan Ryan is a big joke, bad customer service, non speaking English only when they want too, and not to mention how they add up your bill with the calculator, no price for each of the items on the bill, just the total, and they give no receipt. "I'm just saying" I visited there yesterday and it is no longer worth my 48 miles drive.
